@NODE "whatis" "Brief Overview"
@TOC "MAIN"

                           What is Buttonz ?
                           -----------------

Buttonz - developed using Blitz 2.1 - is a full-featured alternative to tools
like ToolsDaemon & ToolsManager. Maybe it's not a direct competitor, but it's
designed to operate in a different, and very intuitive way, and is about as
stable as stable gets.

Buttonz creates a 10 button bank gui (along with a few control gadgets at the
bottom of the window - more on these later) which can each be configured to
launch your favourite programs. Of course having just 10 buttons would be a
bit limited to Amiga users who are used to much more and like to have access
to everything all of the time, so multiple configs are available by launching
into sub-menus from buttons if so desired as can clearly be seen by the example
configuration files within the Buttonz archive.

Buttonz was created as a system friendly commodity with all the functions that
other commodities have and deliberatly uses its own small font for the gui
display to make it as unobtrusive as possible. If you're not using it then
just stab the hotkey to make it dissapear until you need it again. Ideal for
the people like me who prefer an unobtrusive Workbench.


                                @{"Contents Page" LINK "MAIN"}

@ENDNODE

"This space for rent!"

@NODE "instal" "Installation & Requirements"
@TOC "MAIN"

  There is an included install script which uses the new Amiga Technologies
  installer that will simplify this operation for you. If you don't wish to
  use installer (Why?) then you can just drop Buttonz into your WBStartup
  drawer, copy the font into your fonts drawer, and the documentation wherever
  you like (usually Sys:Locale/Help). The config files are there as example
  settings (a direct clone of mine) and you can install them in a directory
  Envarc:Buttonz/ if you wish to have something to start with. If this
  directory is not found when Buttonz is first run then it will create it
  anyway as all config files will be stored there as default. I strongly 
  recommend you keep it this way for easy maintenance.

  This program has been tested on an A500, A600, A2000, A3000 and an A4000.
  It should   work just fine on any Amiga that runs WB2.0+, and we've yet
  to find one it doesn't like yet. It was developed on an A1200 with a
  Blizzard IV-030 and 18 megs of ram.


                                @{"Contents Page" LINK "MAIN"}

@ENDNODE

"Buttonz special edition. Comes with the swear words in the requesters."

@NODE "buttons" "The Main Window Gadgets"
@TOC "MAIN"

Here's a break down of the gadgets and what they do.

  As well as the Buttons themselves, there are three gadgets at the bottom of
the main display window. Store, Quit and Cfg. Store is used to save out the
current configuration loaded (named differently to avoid confusion with the
save button on the prefs window which saves your settings). Quit is pretty
much self-explanatory and Cfg will flip the display to pop up a preferences
display where there are several options for customising how Buttonz works.

Debug     - Set this checkmark if you wish for debug mode to be on. You can
            send me the text this mode generates if you're having problems with
            Buttonz as it may help me sort them out. The file will be in your
            Temp directory which you can configure on this page as well.

Backdrop  - Set this to make Buttonz start up as a backdrop window, meaning it
            will paste itself onto the Workbench screen rather than being a
            moveable window.

NoBorders - Set this to remove the borders of the Buttonz window.

Snapshot  - Set this checkmark and Buttonz will store the X & Y positions of
            the window along with the other preferences.

Active    - Set this if you would like the Buttonz window to become activated
            when it first loads up. Some people use function keys on their
            Workbench and don't like to click outside of windows every time
            they first boot up.

CX Hotkey - Here you can set the hotkey that you can control Buttonz with. It
            uses the RAlt key and whatever you put into this text box.

TempDir   - Click on this button to select a temp directory where Buttonz will
            generate the files it needs. You will find the files to send me
            with debug information in this drawer if debug is switched on.

At the bottom of the prefs window are another 3 gadgets. About, Save and Main.
About will pop up some program information, Save will store the current 
preference settings (Buttonz uses Tooltypes for this - see later documentation)
and Main will return you to the Buttons display.

Buttonz also has a few keyboard shortcuts which you can use.

  Pressing 'H' will pop up a help window giving brief details on the keyboard
               controls and how to configure it.

  Pressing 'S' will pop up the save config requester.

  Pressing 'L' will load the startup configuration (buttonz.bcfg)

  Pressing 'Q' or 'esc' will quit the program.

You can press keys 0 to 9 to launch the appropriate button instead of clicking
on it if you wish.


                                @{"Contents Page" LINK "MAIN"}

@ENDNODE

